JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand steadied against the dollar in early trade on Thursday but looked vulnerable to lingering political tensions after a controversial cabinet reshuffle.At 0640 GMT, the rand traded at 13.8000 per dollar, not far off its overnight close of 13.8100/dollar on Wednesday.South Africa has been in the grip of a political storm since President Jacob Zuma&#8217;s cabinet shake-up triggered a credit downgrade that rocked markets. The ruling ANC party backed Zuma, and rejected calls for the president to quit.&#8220;Local politics clearly remains the major risk, but global risk-off adds some pressure,&#8221; Rand Merchant Bank currency strategists John Cairns said.&#8220;Price action yesterday made it clear that the market has been betting that the president might have to leave office. Such an outcome continues to look unlikely.&#8221;Stocks were set to open lower at 0700 GMT, with the JSE securities exchange&#8217;s Top-40 futures index down 0.46%.In fixed income, the yield for the benchmark government bond due in 2026 rose 3 basis points to 9.035%.